[1] India (Gujarat State)
Date: Tue 7 May 2013
Source: The Times of India (TOI), Times News Network (TNN) [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/City/Rajkot/25-ill-with-typhoid-in-Jamnagar-village/articleshow/19919413.cms


At least 25 people, including 12 children in Dhunvav village, the site for city's [Jamnagar, Gujarat State] garbage dumping, have fallen ill in the last fortnight. While private doctors said they are suffering from typhoid, government health officials are yet to confirm the nature of the disease. It was only after TOI brought to the notice of Jamnagar Municipal Corporation (JMC) notice that medical teams were rushed to the village, which is around 7 km [4.3 mi] from the city.

JMC dumps nearly 200 ton of garbage from Jamnagar in Dhunvav, which is barely 0.5 km [0.3 mi] from the famous Khijadia Bird Sanctuary.

"The garbage has left the drinking water contaminated. It's impossible to sit outside our homes due to the flies," Dhunvav a village sarpanch [an elected head of a village level statutory institution of local self-government called the Panchayat - Mod.LL] said. In fact, she and her husband were among the first to fall ill. "People were falling ill from last 2 months, but it has become severe in last 15 days."

So far 5 patients have been admitted in a private hospital in the city and many are taking local treatment.

[Byline: Darshan Thakker]

