[3] Canada (travelers)
Date: Fri 3 May 2013
Source: Medscape Medical News [edited]
http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/803634


Among children in Canada, most cases of typhoid fever occur after patients travel to endemic areas to visit friends and relatives, according to the findings of a retrospective study. The authors note that recent studies have revealed that typhoid fever can affect children of all ages. "Early studies showed that children and young adults between the ages of 5 and 25 years were the most likely group to be admitted to hospital for typhoid fever; thus, it was thought to be a disease predominantly affecting school-aged and adolescent children," the authors write. "More recently, an Indian study profiling children in hospital in Chennai, India, showed that almost 50 percent of patients in hospital with typhoid fever were 5 years old or younger."

In the current study, the researchers reviewed the records of all patients younger than 18 years who presented to Montreal Children's hospital with a laboratory-confirmed diagnosis of typhoid fever between 1991 and 2011. They identified 39 patients, with a mean patient age of 7.5 years (range, 10 months-17.7 years). Among the cases, 30 occurred in children who had visited an endemic country, most commonly Bangladesh (10 patients), India (8 patients), and Pakistan (5 patients).

Conversely, 4 patients were newly arrived immigrants or refugees from endemic areas. Among the 30 children who contracted typhoid fever while traveling, none had a record of immunization against _Salmonella enterica_ serotype Typhi before departure.

A total of 34 patients required hospital admission for a mean of 8.8 +/- 3.3 days. 36 patients were treated with 3rd-generation cephalosporins, and the mean duration of treatment was 11.8 +/- 4.0 days. In addition, 23 patients received antibiotics before presentation to the hospital. 36 patients had blood samples that were positive for _S._ Typhi, whereas 26 patients had positive stool samples. Among the 39 isolates, 8 were resistant to both ampicillin and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, and 7 were resistant to ciprofloxacin. The most common signs of typhoid fever were anorexia (27 patients), abdominal pain (22 patients), and vomiting (19 patients). In addition, 15 patients had complications after contracting the disease, including hepatitis (4 patients), coagulopathy (3 patients), and meningitis (2 patients).

"The availability of 2 approved vaccines makes this disease potentially preventable for travelers," the authors write. "Family physicians and pediatricians should emphasize the risk of typhoid fever and other travel-related infections (such as malaria) to their patients, especially children whose parents are from endemic areas. This counselling, which should include discussion about safe foods and water, as well as sanitation and hygiene, may be part of regularly scheduled appointments, because parents may not seek medical advice before travelling to their home country."

[Byline: Joe Barber Jr]

